<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Top 50 Construction Firms' Orders Said Down </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101133394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1240 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 31 KYODO -- Orders won in 1993 by 
Japan's 50 major construction companies totaled 19.73 trillion 
yen, an 18.2 percent fall from the previous year and the second 
consecutive yearly decline, the Construction Ministry announced 
Monday [31 January]. 
  The rate of decline was the greatest since the ministry 
started the annual surveys in 1961. 
  Ministry officials attributed the plunge chiefly to a 24.1 
percent fall in construction orders from the private sector to 
12.11 trillion yen -- the third straight yearly drop. 
  Orders from the manufacturing industries, centered on the 
automotive and food businesses, posted a 37.1 percent decrease, 
and those from the nonmanufacturing industries a 21.3 percent 
fall. 
  Orders from the public sector totaled 6.38 trillion yen, 
down 
7.1 percent for the first fall in eight years. 
  Authorities placed more orders with medium-sized and small 
construction companies and fewer orders with major firms 
following the uncovering last year of a series of bribery 
scandals involving general contractors and local government 
chiefs. 

</TEXT>

