<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Commentary on Stimulus Package Issue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Cabinet on Tax Cut Link to Hike </H4>
<F P=102> OW0102014394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0138 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102014394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 1 KYODO -- Cabinet members agreed with 
the Finance Ministry that a law to cut income taxes aimed at 
stimulating the economy must also contain a provision calling 
for an offsetting rise in the consumption tax, Finance Minister 
Hirohisa Fujii said Tuesday [1 February]. 
  Fujii told a regular press conference after the morning 
cabinet meeting that he asked cabinet members to "reaffirm" that 
the two be handled together and that there were "no objections." 
The issue has split government and ruling party leaders in 
recent days, with many calling for an early tax cut while 
leaving for the future the matter of how to pay for it. 
  Fujii also said he interpreted comments made Monday by 
Deputy 
Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata to mean that a joint economic forum 
between the government and the coalition has "decided" that the 
tax cut and hike will be linked. 
  After a forum meeting, Hata told reporters that "tax cuts 
without future (funding) expectations are dangerous for the 
nation," adding that "it is necessary to indicate a set 
direction" for handling the consumption tax matter. Hata said 
the forum would issue its final decision by Wednesday. 
  Fujii said the stimulus package, to be announced Thursday, 
would be "large-scale," hinting that it will exceed September's 
record 13.2 trillion yen package. He said he hopes it will be 
the last such package needed to get Japan's sluggish economy on 
track for full-fledged recovery in the fiscal year starting in 
April and stable growth in the following fiscal year. 
  Fujii said Japan's economy is not in such dire straits as to 
require a stimulus financed by deficit spending that would erode 
the nation's fiscal position and later prove to be a "disgrace" 
to the financial authorities. Although he does not think the 
economy has hit bottom, he noted that Bank of Japan Governor 
Yasushi Mieno reported signs last week that corporate sentiment 
is improving. 
  Fujii repeated that the same tax reform package that cuts 
taxes must include the "timing and new rate" of the consumption 
tax increase to guarantee repayment of any short-term bonds 
issued to finance the cut. To support his concern about deficit 
spending, he cited a report by the Paris-based Organization for 
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) which he said proves 
the Japanese Government's consolidated fiscal position has 
become "the worst among the leading nations." 
  He said "the world misunderstands" the issue, apparently 
referring to a U.S. Government contention that Japan has fiscal 
breathing room to cut income taxes without linking the move 
directly to a consumption tax hike. 
  Fujii also said he would carefully watch long-term interest 
rates, which have recently begun to edge up, but he played down 
concerns that such upward pressure would put a drag on the 
economy, saying the government will not issue any bonds that 
cannot be "digested" by the market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

