<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Commentary on Stimulus Package Issue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Parties Postpone Tax Decision </H4>
<F P=102> OW0102120594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1139 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 1 KYODO -- Ruling coalition parties on 
Tuesday [1 February] remained divided on how to finance a 
proposed income tax cut and postponed a final decision until 
Wednesday, party officials said. Although coalition party 
representatives met twice, they failed to reach a conclusion due 
to a gulf over whether to offset the proposed income tax 
reduction with a hike in the consumption tax, the officials said. 
  Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general of Shinseito (the Japan 
Renewal Party), told reporters the meetings broke down, adding 
that the ruling parties will hold another round of talks on 
Wednesday to thrash out a decision. 
  "It all depends on the SDP (Social Democratic Party)," said 
Takashi Yonezawa, secretary general of the Democratic Socialist 
Party. 
  The SDP, the largest force in the seven-party coalition 
government, has objected to the idea of raising the consumption 
tax, presently at 3 percent, to cover the diminished revenue 
resulting from the proposed income tax cut. 
  The income tax reduction is expected to be the core of a 
fresh economic stimulus package to be finalized by Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's cabinet on Thursday. 
  SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama told reporters later that the 
party is willing to consider a more balanced tax system but 
oppose the consumption tax hike coupled in the same package with 
an income tax reduction. 
  He indicated it is acceptable to issue relatively short-term 
national bonds, like those that mature in five years, to fund 
tax cuts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

