<H3> <TI>   More Commentary on Stimulus Package Issue </TI></H3>
<H4>   LDP Special Panel Adopts Program </H4>
<F P=102> OW0102133294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1309 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 1 KYODO -- The opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party decided Tuesday [1 February] to ask the 
coalition government of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa to 
implement a 15 trillion yen economic stimulus package, party 
officials said. The officials said the request will be made by 
party leader Yohei Kono at his meeting with Hosokawa on 
Wednesday afternoon. 
  The program, adopted at the party's special panel to combat 
the recession, partly reflects a proposal made by Michio 
Watanabe, a senior member of the party and former foreign 
minister, they said. His 20 trillion yen proposal incorporated 
income and local tax cuts totaling about 10 trillion yen, they 
said. 
  But the LDP will only request an "early implementation of 
sharp tax cuts," they said. The officials said the LDP program 
also calls for a substantial reduction or a freeze of the land 
value tax. 

</TEXT>

