<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Commentary on Stimulus Package Issue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Government Eyes 1-Year Deadline </H4>
<F P=102> OW0102153594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1522 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102153594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 1 KYODO -- The government is moving to 
set a one-year deadline for deciding an overall tax policy over 
which the ruling coalition remains split, a senior Shinseito 
(Japan Renewal Party) official said Tuesday. 
  A compromise plan is gaining ground among the seven-party 
coaltion after coalition party representatives failed to narrow 
the gap over whether to offset the proposed income tax reduction 
with a hike in the consumption tax, the official said. Under 
the plan, the government would issue a statement that would say 
the government should reach within a year a final decision on 
basic tax reform policy including revision of the ratio of 
direct to indirect taxes in the total tax revenues. 
  The plan also calls for the establishment of a special forum 
within the coalition to discuss the problem. 
  The government failed to reach an agreement on the issue due 
mainly to opposition by the Social Democratic Party to raising 
the consumption tax from the current 3 percent to finance the 
planned tax cuts. 
  The forthcoming package of economic stimulus measures will 
include income and resident tax cuts worth over 7 trillion yen, 
the Shinseito official said. 

</TEXT>

