<H3> <TI>   IAEA Spokesman: DPRK May Suspend Nuclear Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0102005094 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0005 GMT 1 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0102005094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Yi Il-hwa from Tokyo] </F>
  [Text] According to a TOKYO SHIMBUN report dispatched from 
Vienna on 1 February, David Kyd, International Atomic Energy 
Agency [IAEA] spokesman, said that North Korea may announce it 
will suspend negotiations on the nuclear inspection issue in the 
next talks scheduled this week on North Korea permitting nuclear 
inspections. 
  Spokesman Kyd said: The IAEA has already explained to North 
Korea the details of procedures for nuclear inspections. North 
Korea is expected to respond before the end of this week. The 
IAEA cannot make any concessions in its original plan for 
inspections [tangcho-e chesihan sachal naeyongul chogumdo 
yangbohalsu opta]. 
  Spokesman Kyd also said: If North Korea's response is 
negative [pujongjok] or clearly shows its aim to stall for time, 
the IAEA will stop holding negotiations with North Korea and 
will inform the United States of this. 
  Information Director Kyd said that the IAEA will discuss the 
North Korean nuclear issue again in its Board of Governors 
regular meeting to be held beginning 21 February. 

</TEXT>

