<H3> <TI>   Ex-President Attempts Contact With Former Aide </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0102062194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0534 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0102062194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 1 (YONHAP) -- Kim Chong-hwi, the former 
presidential aide who has bolted the country to avoid 
prosecution on charges of accepting bribes, was preparing to 
settle down with his family in the United States last December 
when he invited his son and daughter-in-law to live there, it 
was disclosed Tuesday. 
  Meanwhile, former President No Tae-u, aware of mounting 
public criticism against his former secretary for foreign and 
national security affairs, is trying to contact Kim to persuade 
him not to seek permanent residency in the United States, 
sources said. 
  No, who had been indifferent to the issue until recently, 
was 
unsuccessful in his attempt to get in touch with Kim in the 
United States, they said. 
  Kim left the country shortly after he was implicated in an 
investigation of alleged irregularities in the Yulgok project, 
and was reported in recent weeks to have applied for permanent 
U.S. residency or even political asylum. 
  One aide to No said Tuesday he fears that the former 
president may ultimately have to take responsibility if Kim 
fails to return to Korea. That's why "we have been asking 
around if people know the whereabouts of Kim, but so far they 
are not known," he added. 
  It was disclosed belatedly that Kim's 27-year-old son and 
his 
wife suddenly left the country for the United States at the end 
of last December and speculation abounds here now that Kim had 
already made careful preparations to settle down in the United 
States for good. 

</TEXT>

