<H3> <TI>   U.S. Ambassador Quoted on Human Rights in North </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0102092794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0900 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0102092794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 1 (YONHAP) -- U.S. Ambassador to South 
Korea James T. Laney said on Tuesday that North Korea should 
ease tensions by opening up its nuclear program. Laney, in a 
speech prepared for delivery at a dinner meeting hosted by the 
Korean-American Association Tuesday afternoon, said North Korea 
also "should begin to open its economy, and move as quickly as 
possible to grant its people those civil and human rights which 
are, after all, the reason governments are instituted among men." 
  At the meeting held in the Hyatt Hotel in downtown Seoul, he 
said, "I have a personal image of the contrast between the world 
built by communist societies and that we enjoy in the free 
world... North Korea is on the sad side of this contrast. They 
must come to terms with this fact." 
  He added that South Korea has to come to terms with its own 
new self. 
  "I want to urge you to embrace the status you've earned as 
one of the world's leaders... So when I urge you to accept and 
believe in the Korea that you've built, I'm hoping that your 
acceptance will lead you to embrace the responsibilities of a 
world leader," he said. 

</TEXT>

