<H3> <TI>   Rent for U.S. Embassy To Be Collected Retroactively </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2901115394 Seoul YONHAP in English 1144 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2901115394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 29 (YONHAP) -- The government has 
decided to collect rents for U.S. Embassy buildings here in 
Seoul retroactively to the past five years and in the future and 
inform shortly the U.S. Government of the decision, a Foreign 
Ministry official said over the weekend. He added the 
government would start negotiations with the U.S. Government on 
the matter during next week, if things go smoothly. 
  The Board of Audit and Inspection noted last July that the 
U.S. Government had not paid rents for its embassy buildings for 
the past 13 years without any legal basis. 
  The government has concluded that it is reasonable to 
collect 
retroactive rents for the past five years and continue to 
collect new rents in the future, the official said. 
  The government will also request that the U.S. Government 
move the embassy to the old site of Kyonggi Girls High School as 
soon as possible, he added. The rents are estimated at about 
500 million won a year. The U.S. Government is expected to 
claim the right to use the buildings free of rents. 

</TEXT>

