<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Country To `Fully Liberalize' Travel to China </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3101132294 Seoul YONHAP in English 1049 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3101132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 31 (YONHAP) -- The government on Monday 
decided to fully liberalize travels to China by South Koreans in 
the foreseeable future. The decision was made at a meeting of 
working-level officials from relevant government offices. It 
was presided over by Vice Foreign Minister Hong Sun-yong. 
  The meeting did not set the time of China trip 
liberalization, but an informed source said the time would 
possibly be two months later, the end of March. 
  "At the meeting, attendees agreed to liberalize South 
Koreans' travels to China at the soonest early date and left the 
determining of the time to the Foreign Ministry," an official 
said. He added that to facilitate free trips to China, there 
should first be some security precautionary measures such as 
steps to keep people from illegally entering North Korea by way 
of China. 
  "Given the time needed to prepare such steps, we believe 
travels to China could be liberalized toward the end of March," 
he said. 
  Presently, a person wishing to visit China, Cuba, Laos or 
Cambodia should obtain an invitation from an organization or 
firm of the country he likes to visit and then obtain a 
government permit to go. 

</TEXT>

