<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul, Beijing Agree on Air Traffic Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3101020594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0103 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3101020594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 31 (YONHAP) -- While tentatively 
agreeing to open regular direct air services between their two 
capitals South Korea and China have decided not to grant one 
another beyond-point traffic rights that permit flights through 
their respective airspace for travel to third-country 
destinations, informed sources here said Monday. 
  Thus when the Seoul-Beijing route opens, which may take 
place 
as early as April, Europe-bound Korean Airlines cannot fly over 
China and Chinese carriers are not permitted to use Korean 
airspace for travel to the United States or Japan, the sources 
said. 
  "We (Seoul and Beijing) did agree on having beyond-point 
traffic rights in principle, but we decided to apply the rights 
in the future when we find them necessary," a Seoul government 
official said. 
  The two governments agreed not to initiate beyond-point 
traffic rights at present because when they do, the 
Seoul-Beijing route could become an international one as it may 
be opened to other airlines and they fear a loss of passengers, 
he said. 
  They reached tentative agreement on opening a direct air 
route between the two capitals after a week of working-level 
talks in Beijing that started Jan. 17. 
  The agreement is expected to be put into writing next month 
in the fifth bilateral aviation talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

