<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul, PRC Agree To Restore Historical Building </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2901021494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0054 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2901021494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 29 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and China 
have agreed to restore the building used by the Korean 
provisional government in Chongqing, China, by Aug. 15 next 
year, a Foreign Ministry official said Saturday. 
  When Japan annexed Korea in 1910 and ruled the country until 
1945, Korean independence fighters set up a government-in-exile 
in Shanghai, China. They later moved it to Chongqing along with 
the Chinese nationalist party, when the Japanese invaded China. 
  "Seoul and Beijing agreed to restore the building of the 
Korean provisional government in Chongqing last December and the 
restoration work will begin in the first half of this year and 
will be completed by Aug. 15 next year," the official said. 
  Aug. 15 is the day when Korea gained independence from Japan 
in 1945 at the end of the World War II. 
  "The area near the site of the Korean provisional government 
in Chongqing is to be demolished for land development, but Seoul 
and Beijing have agreed to restore the building of the Korean 
provisional government. Seoul will invest 1.3 million U.S. 
dollars for it and Beijing will chip in 2 million dollars," he 
said. 
  The premises will include two four-story structures and two 
two-story buildings with an aggregate floor space of 1,712 
square meters. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-27905 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas021_d_94029" </HT>


