<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Philippines President Meets Kim Yong-sam </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2901091794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0826 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2901091794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 29 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam 
and former Philippine President Corazon Aquino exchanged 
opinions on democracy, reforms and Philippine workers in Korea 
during their meeting at Chongwadae [presidential office] on 
Saturday morning. 
  "I know well that you've contributed much to the 
democratization process in your country," Kim told her, "and I 
gave my spiritual support to your democratization movement at 
the time. I was also in the democratization movement in Korea 
and I know well the difficulties you must have had in that 
movement." 
  Noting that some 15,000 Philippine workers are in Korea now, 
Kim said he had instructed the cabinet to take steps to improve 
working conditions of foreign workers to the level of those for 
domestic workers, including a step for foreign workers to 
benefit from the industrial accident insurance system, 
Chongwadae Spokesman Chu Ton-sik said. 
  "Our trade with China has exceeded the 
10-billion-U.S.-dollar 
mark, though we established diplomatic relations only two years 
ago," Kim said, "but the trade between Korea and the Philippines 
is slow in growth, compared with a long history of relations 
between the two countries." 
  The former Philippine president said she would tell 
President 
Fidel Ramos to take measures for increased trade with South 
Korea and asked for special consideration of Philippine workers, 
as there would be more and more foreign workers in Korea in the 
future. 
  When Kim thanks her for Philippine support in the Korean 
war, 
she said her husband, the late Sen. Aquino, had been a war 
correspondent during the war, and added, "because of this he won 
many votes in elections." 
  Many leaders of the world consider President Kim's political 
reforms as a model for them, she told Kim. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

