<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry To Reduce Number of Senior Officials </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0102033594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0257 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0102033594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 1 (YONHAP) -- The Foreign Ministry may 
decide to reduce the number of vice minister-level senior 
officials at the special grade one level by three to four a year 
over five years in a bid to cut staff and rationalize the 
organization's structure, officials said Tuesday. The Ministry 
is studying ways to eliminate the posts of 17 senior officials, 
according to the official. 
  A senior official at the Ministry said, "there has been 
criticism that the Ministry has too many special grade one 
officials and too few working-level officials. 
  "A recent meeting of the Ministry's senior officials almost 
agreed to the reduction of the organization's staff. If things 
go well, we plan to receive approval from the minister and 
revise the executive ordinance of the Public Servants' Law 
covering foreign affairs. We want to begin the reduction within 
the first half of this year." 
  Other ministries do not have the positions of special grade 
one or two level officials, which are unique to the Foreign 
Ministry. 
  Under the plan, the number of special grade one level 
officials will decrease from 47 to 30 over five years, while 
that of special grade two level officials at the assistant 
minister level will be maintained at the current 35. 
  In contrast, the number of grade one level officials will 
rise from the current 53 to 70. 

</TEXT>

