<H3> <TI>   Retired Opposition Leader Departs for Europe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2901103894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0925 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2901103894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 29 (YONHAP) -- Retired opposition leader 
Kim Tae-chung left Seoul Saturday for 10-day visits to Norway, 
Sweden and Denmark. Kim, who is chairman of Board of Directors 
of the Kim Tae-chung Peace Foundation, is scheduled first to go 
to Norway where he will meet with Foreign Minister Jan Egeland 
and other senior government officials, lawmakers, journalists 
for exchanging views of mutual interests. 
  In Sweden, Kim will meet with Vice Prime Minister Bengt 
Westerberg, Foreign Minister Margaretha Ugglas and Chairman of 
Foreign Affairs Committee of Legislature Daniel Tarschys. 
  In Denmark, he plans to meet with Foreign Minister Niels 
Helveg Petersen and will give a speech at Foreign Policy Council 
with a theme "roads to unification of the Korean peninsula." 
  Chairman of the main opposition Democratic Party Yi Ki-taek, 
visited Kim's home at Tonggyo-tong, western Seoul, Saturday 
morning and bid bon voyage to Kim. 

