<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Consumer Prices Rise 1.3 Percent in January </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0102025794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0159 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0102025794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 1 (YONHAP) -- Consumer and producer 
prices in January rose 1.3 percent and 1.1 percent, 
respectively, from December, according to the National 
Statistical Office and the Bank of Korea. 
  The figures were up 0.5 percentage point from the increase 
recorded a year earlier for consumer prices and 0.7 percentage 
point for producer prices, largely due to higher oil, cigarette 
and farm prices. Farm prices rose 3.7 percent and livestock 
prices went up 1.7 percent, while fish prices dipped 0.3 
percent. Fresh food prices as a whole surged 3.9 percent 
compared with the 3.6 percent registered in January last year. 
  Processed food prices inched up 0.7 percent and public 
utility charges increased 1.3 percent. 
  Steel prices rose, while the prices of whiskey, video-tape 
recorders and ready-made concrete fell. 
  Chong Chae-yong, the Economic Planning Board official in 
charge of price policy, on Tuesday blamed higher cigarette and 
oil taxes and the lean crops caused by last year's cold summer 
for the sharp consumer price hike in January, but said prices 
would stablize in the second quarter to record a six-percent 
increase for the whole of this year, the same inflation level as 
last year. 

</TEXT>

