<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   Statistics Department Reports Trade Surplus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0102101694 Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES in English 29 
Jan 94 p 18 </F>

<F P=103> BK0102101694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Malaysia achieved a trade surplus of RM3.9 
billion [Malaysian currency] for January to October 1993, 
compared with a smaller surplus of RM648.2 million during the 
corresponding period of 1992. 
  The Statistics Department reported that the improved trade 
position was due to stronger demand, which induced higher export 
growth compared with that of imports. Exports expanded by 18 
percent from the 10 months in 1992 to RM100.2 billion as against 
a 14.3 percent growth in imports at RM96.3 billion. [passage 
omitted] 
  For the 10-month period under review, the acceleration of 
export growth was largely contributed by significant increases 
in the exports of manufactured goods (+36.8 percent), machinery 
and transport equipment (+29.7 percent) and miscellaneous 
manufactured articles (+10.7 percent). These three major 
components contributed to 67.9 percent of total export earnings. 
  The department reported that exports of mineral fuel, the 
second largest contributor to export value, experienced a 
reduction of 5.2 percent in earnings when compared with the same 
period in 1992. 
  The growth in imports was largely contributed by higher 
imports of machinery and transport equipment (+16.6 percent), 
which accounted for 55.7 percent of total import receipts. 
  Malaysia's major trading partners during January-October 
1993 
were Japan, the United States, Singapre, Taiwan, Germany, the 
United Kingdom, South Korea and Hong Kong, which collectively 
accounted for 75.4 percent of the total trade. 

</TEXT>

