<H3> <TI>   Hata Reacts to PKO Participation in Yugoslavia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101002894 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3101002894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime minister and foreign 
minister, gave a news conference in his capacity as head of 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] at the Diet building on 29 
January. Touching on the question of Japan's sending personnel 
to the former Yugoslavia to participate in UN Peacekeeping 
Operations (PKO), Hata said: "From an official standpoint, the 
overall situation has not met with the five principles on PKO 
participation (such as a cease-fire accord) yet. We will have 
to clarify this point." Thus, he indicated his view that the 
current situation in the former Yugoslavia does not fulfill the 
five principles. 

</TEXT>

