1986-1992. 




Table 3. Changes in Japan's Principal Exports (Unit: $100 million) 

                      1986     1987     1988     1989     1990     1991     1992 

Total exported        2,092    2,292    2,649    2,752    2,869    3,145    3,396 
amount 

Finished products 

Automobiles No.       427      449      488      485      510      548      605 
cars (10,000)         701      655      636      616      616      607      600 

Office equipment      113      144      184      193      206      222      254 

Scientific/optical    85       94       108      112      116      129      135 
equipment 

Steel                 127      126      153      148      125      136      133 

Video equipment       114      102      121      116      131      140      122 

Parts 

Semiconductors,       63       83       123      141      133      149      175 
electronic parts 

Automobile parts      82       107      91       99       109      113      125 

Engines               49       59       67       75       77       83       97 

Source: Ministry of Finance trade statistics 


  During the early half of the 1980's (specifically, in 1980, 
1981, and 1982), the number of imports fell but, from 1986, has 
been increasing at a higher rate due to expanding domestic 
demand (Table 1 and 2). Specifically, from the latter half of 
the 1980's, clothing, office machinery (such as computers), 
semiconductors and electronic parts (such as integrated 
circuits) and audio-video equipment (color televisions, VTR's) 
have all shown significant increases (Table 4). 
  The decline in the volume of manufactured imported products 
in 1992 was due to a decline in luxury items such as cars, gold, 
diamonds and paintings as well as in steel and nonferrous metals 
(aluminum, aluminum alloys, copper and copper alloys), the 
result of the bubble economy's collapse and the domestic 
economy's entering an adjustment phase. Where local production 
by Japanese enterprises had progressed--in apparel, office 
equipment, semiconductors and electronic parts, and audio and 
video equipment--imports continued to increase. 
  Behind such changes in the trade structure, we can find the 
influence of the yen's sharp rise in value following the Plaza 
Accord of 1985. The yen's appreciation lowered import prices 
(calculated on the basis of the yen) and weakened the ability of 
domestically manufactured goods to remain price-competitive. In 
order to respond to the yen's sharp rise and deal with trade 
problems, however, Japanese enterprises aggressively engaged in 
foreign direct investments and succeeded in transferring their 
production bases overseas. 
  As a result, re-imported products--for the most part mass 
market consumer products--penetrated the domestic market while 
exports, in order to keep the work force employed at home, 
centered on high value added items that could not be produced at 
overseas plants, thus creating specialization, or an 
international division of labor, in the production of 
manufactured goods. In the future, too, domestic and foreign 
economic trends permitting, Japanese enterprises are expected to 
expand their overseas operations even further, just as they have 
since the latter half of the 1980's, as long as yen continues 
its upward climb. 


Table 4. Changes in Japan's Principal Manufactured Imports (Unit: $100 
million) 

                   1986    1987    1988    1989     1990     1991     1992 

Total exported     528     660     918     1,061    1,180    1,203    1,170 
amount 

Consumer, capital goods 

Apparel            29      46      67      89       87       93       112 

Office equipment   17      22      33      44       52       56       60 


Semiconductors,    12      15      23      29       33       39       40 
electronic parts 


Aircraft           18      17      20      17       32       32       32 

Audio, video       4       8       14      19       18       22       25 
equipment 

Luxury items 

Automobiles        11      21      32      42       64       54       52 

Gold               70      35      41      35       36       26       20 

Diamonds           9       14      21      22       25       21       18 

Paintings          3       8       14      21       34       7        3 

Steel, nonferrous metals 

Steel              18      25      46      51       46       55       38 

Aluminum,          16      27      50      51       48       46       36 
aluminum alloys 

Copper, copper     5       7       13      17       19       18       11 
alloys 

Source: Ministry of Finance trade statistics 


  This article will first examine trends in Japanese foreign 
direct investments, the engine behind changes in Japan's trade 
structure, in three areas: North America, Europe and Asia. A 
larger share of all foreign direct investments during the latter 
half of the 1980's was going to Asia, reflecting the importance 
placed on this region in the corporate strategies of Japanese 
enterprises. While we can gather from their profits that 
Japanese-owned enterprises engaged in local production in Europe 
and the United States are having a hard time, operations in Asia 
are proceeding smoothly, comparatively speaking, and in the 
future, we can expect the relative importance of this region for 
Japanese enterprises to increase even further. 
  Wide variations exist among different industries when it 
comes to local production. The picture, however, in terms of 
changes in trade structure due to foreign direct investments, 
when considered on an industry by industry basis (here, the 
automobile, consumer appliance and electronics, apparel, and 
steel industries will be considered), indicates that in each of 
these industries, manufacturers are exporting high value added 
products. On the other hand, the trend in imports is toward mass 
distribution consumer products. Thus, we can see that, in terms 
of exports and imports, an international division of labor, or 
"segregation of niche" [sumiwake] is developing. 
  During the latter half of the 1980's, a large wave of 
foreign 
direct investments was developing, even on an international 
scale, (with investments going from advanced countries to other 
advanced countries and from advanced countries to developing 
nations), and as a result, there has been a shift in the world's 
trade structure, including Japan's, from vertical to horizontal 
trade. This shift can be understood in terms of changes in the 
index of intra-industry trade (ITT), an indicator of the degree 
to which horizontal (intra-industry) trade has developed. Not 
only has Asia, a region actively receiving direct investments 
from advanced nations, including Japan, seen a brisk, quickening 
of trade, close trading ties within the region are developing as 
domestic demand among Asian countries expands. Changes in 
Japan's trade structure and in its regional ties can also be 
seen from the perspective of Japan's international air cargo. 
<H5>  II. Trends in Japanese Foreign Direct Investments </H5>
  1. General Remarks 
  From the end of the 1980's into the 1990's, foreign direct 
investments by Japanese enterprises have increased dramatically 
as companies have embarked on plans to transfer their domestic 
production bases overseas. This move has been in response to a 
downturn in the profitability of exports due to the yen's steep 
rise following the 1985 Plaza Accord and in response to 
voluntary export restrictions and worsening trade relations of 
the kind seen in anti-dumping suits (Table 5). 


---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Table 5. Changes in Japanese Foreign Direct Investments (Manufacturing In-| 
|dustry) (Unit: $100 million; percent)                                     | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Fiscal year   |World total   |North America |Europe        |Asia          | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|1986          |38.6 (100)    |22.0 (58)     |3.7 (10)      |8.0 (21)      | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|1987          |78.3 (100)    |48.5 (62)     |8.5 (11)      |16.8 (21)     | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|1988          |138.1 (100)   |91.9 (67)     |15.5 (11)     |23.7 (17)     | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|1989          |162.8 (100)   |95.8 (59)     |30.9 (19)     |32.2 (20)     | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|1990          |154.9 (100)   |67.9 (44)     |45.9 (30)     |30.7 (20)     | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|1991          |123.1 (100)   |58.7 (48)     |26.9 (22)     |29.3 (24)     | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|1992          |100.6 (100)   |41.8 (42)     |21.0 21)      |31.0 (31)     | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Source: Ministry of Finance (Zaisei kinyu tokei geppo [Monthly fiscal mon-| 
|etary statistical report; hereafter, Monthly Statistical Report], etc.)   | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Note 1: Figures in parentheses ( ) indicate regional percent of all forei-| 
|gn direct investments.                                                    | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Note 2: North America covers the United States and Canada; Europe include-| 
|s the European Community, European Free Trade Association [EFTA], the for-| 
|mer Soviet Union and East Germany; Asia includes Asian newly industrializ-| 
|ing economies [NIE's], ASEAN, and Pakistan.                               | 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  Amounting to just $3.9 billion in 1986, foreign direct 
investments by Japanese manufacturing industries rose to $16.3 
billion in 1989, reaching an all time high. Although investments 
have dropped since 1990 for various reasons--the increasingly 
unpredictable nature of market trends due to a global slump, the 
difficulty of raising corporate funds following the collapse of 
Japan's bubble economy, and the completion of a round of plans 
by Japanese companies to build overseas production bases--the 
level of investments, in 1992 amounting to $10.1 million, still 
remains high when compared to the early half of the 1980's when 
investments were at around the $3 billion level. (It should be 
noted that, after an initial period of investments in local 
production, additional funds for plant facilities are often 
raised by companies in the country where those facilities are 
located and the connection between direct investments from Japan 
and the further development of local production becomes weaker.) 
  In considering regional changes in Japan's foreign direct 
investments, we see that North America was Japan's principal 
target for investors, their reasons for investing in this region 
being to maintain and expand their market shares and to develop 
new markets; additionally, investors have been motivated by the 
desire to avoid trade problems. As can be seen in responses to 
the questionnaire given to Japanese enterprises on their reasons 
for branching out overseas (Table 6), oftentimes the motive, in 
the case of North America and Europe was to cope with trade 
restrictions set up by their trading partners. In 1988, 67 
percent of [Japan's] foreign direct investments went to North 
America, but that figure has since dropped, falling to 42 
percent in 1992. Among the reasons for this decline are the 
business slump in the United States and the fact that Japanese 
enterprises have just finished a round of large-scale production 
projects (Table 7). 
  Europe's share of foreign direct investments, about 10 
percent, was relatively low until 1988, but with the economic 
unification of the European Community (EC) slated for 1992, 
Japanese-owned enterprises, believing they should try to gain 
"insider status," hurriedly began to move into the region from 
the latter half of the 1980's, bringing EC's share of Japanese 
investments to 30 percent in 1990. Because of the business slump 
in Europe, particularly in England, which receives from 
one-third to one-fourth of the direct investments from Japan 
(Table 7), less money is being invested in the area, and 
Europe's share dropped to 21 percent in 1992. 
  Ideally, there are two routes companies can take when moving 
into advanced market countries (i.e., North America and Europe): 
they can either set up their own production bases there through 
foreign direct investments (local production) or they can base 
their production on tie-ups with [local] enterprises (establish 
mutually complementary production relationships, OEM [original 
equipment manufacturer] tie-ups, technical tie-ups, or joint 
development). In recent years, rather than through foreign 
direct investments, more weight has been given to the latter 
route; namely, cooperative dealings between companies and joint 
technical development based on strategic tie-ups with foreign 
enterprises. As a result, Japanese companies have been placing 
less importance on foreign direct investments. 
  Asia, with its abundance of cheap labor, on the other hand, 
has been designated a production base for Japanese-owned 
enterprises and since 1988, has steadily been receiving a larger 
share of Japan's foreign direct investments. In 1992, this share 
reached an all time high of 31 percent. But even within the same 
region, interest has been shifting since 1990 from ASEAN 
[Association of Southeast Asian Nation] member countries to 
China. Thus, it seems that in recent years, Japan's foreign 
direct investments have been shifting from North America and 
Europe to Asia. 


