  2. Regional Trends in Japanese Foreign Direct 
Investments and the Earnings Situation of Japanese-Owned 
Enterprises 
  If we consider regional trends in foreign direct investments 
in terms of profits, we see that, according to a questionnaire 
survey (on the overseas business activities of Japanese 
companies), which was conducted by the Ministry of International 
Trade and Industry [MITI], current profit-to-sales ratios for 
companies in North America and Europe are low and, in some 
cases, companies are even coming out with negative profit 
ratios. In Asia, on the other hand, current profit ratios for 
Japanese-owned companies are relatively high (Table 8). 


Table 8. Changes in Current Profit-Sales Ratios of Overseas Japanese 
Enterprises (Manufacturing Industry) (Unit: percent) 

                 1986      1987      1988      1989      1990      1991 

World ratio      1.4       2.2       2.9       1.8       1.8       0.9 

North America    0.7       0.4       0.7       0.2       -0.9      -1.9 

Europe           1.2       2.0       2.3       2.3       3.2       -0.6 

Asia             2.3       4.0       4.4       3.8       5.0       4.8 

All domestic     2.8       3.7       4.5       4.7       4.3       3.4 
enterprises 

Source: Ministry of Finance (Hojin kigyo tokei [Corporate statistics], 
etc.) 


  [Text]North America 
  In North America, current profit-to-sales ratios for 
Japanese-owned enterprises have been low, especially since 1990, 
when the situation took a sharp turn for the worse, and in 1992, 
a negative 1.9 percent figure was recorded. The following are 
among the factors thought to be responsible: 
  (1) North America was hit by a business recession during 
the start up period for large scale projects 
  (2) In order to manufacture high quality goods on a scale 
beyond a certain level, Japanese companies that have gone to 
North America often have capital-intensive facilities and, 
during their start-up period, have high depreciation costs and 
are also burdened by heavy interest payments. 
  Again, local sales ratios for Japanese-owned enterprises in 
North America are about 90 percent, and presumably having 
invested in order to secure a share of the local market, they 
may be sacrificing profits to a certain extent when they make 
their investments (Table 9.1). 



  Table 9.1. Changes in Percent of Products Sold in Local Markets by 
Overseas Japanese Companies: North America (Unit: percent) 

               1986      1987      1988      1989      1990      1991 

Products for   92.8      92.8      93.8      93.1      90.1      89.4 
local 
markets 

Exports for    7.2       7.2       6.2       6.9       9.9       10.6 
non-local 
markets 

Exports for    3.3       4.8       4.0       4.5       3.3       4.1 
Japanese 
market 

Source: MITI (Overseas Business Activities of Japanese Enterprises) 


  According to a survey conducted by the U.S. Department of 
Commerce regarding profits from foreign investments in the 
United States (Survey of Current Business, August 1992), the 
rate of return on investments by resident foreign enterprises 
falls below returns on the domestic and foreign investments of 
U.S. companies, leading one to suspect that low returns on 
investments in the United States are not a problem that only 
affects Japanese-owned enterprises (Table 10). 


Table 10. Comparison of Rates of Return on U.S. Investments Abroad and 
Foreign Investments in U.S. (Based on Market Values) (Unit: percent) 

                1986      1987      1988      1989      1990      1991 

Overseas        7.2       7.7       8.4       7.9       7.6       6.9 
production by 
U.S. 
companies 

U.S.            2.2       2.5       3.9       2.2       -0.3      -0.2 
production by 
non-U.S. 
companies 

U.S.            7.2       8.1       9.0       7.6       7.7       6.0 
production by 
U.S. 
companies 

Source: U.S. Dept. of Commerce (Survey of Current Business, August 1992) 

Note: Rate of return = Sales/Total Assets 


  [Text] 
Europe 
  Current profit-to-sales ratios in Europe, though lower than 
in Japan for all domestic companies, were indicating profits 
until 1992 when, due to the recession, companies began showing 
negative returns and negative profit ratios of 0.6 percent. As 
in the case of North America, many of the companies branching 
out into Europe were doing so in response to trade problems 
related to automobiles and scientific and optical equipment such 
as duplicators and copying machines; but, for the most part, as 
concern grew about the "fortification of Europe" with the 
approaching unification of the EC in 1992, companies beat a 
hasty path to this region during the closing years of the 1980's 
in order to gain insider status so they could secure a piece of 
the European market. 
  Over 90 percent of the sales of locally produced goods in 
Europe comes from local markets. As in the case of the United 
States, Europe is not a manufacturing base for exports to 
countries, including Japan, that are outside of the region 
(Table 9.2) 


Table 9.2. Changes in Percent of Products Sold in Local Markets by 
Overseas Japanese Enterprises: Europe (Unit: percent) 

               1986      1987      1988      1989      1990      1991 

Products for   95.9      95.9      94.4      95.6      96.1      93.9 
local 
markets 

Exports for    4.1       5.6       4.4       3.9       3.9       6.1 
non-local 
markets 

Exports for    1.2       1.5       1.7       1.7       1.2       1.9 
Japanese 
markets 


  Asia 
  Not only are current profit-to-sales ratios higher in Asia 
than in North America and Europe, in 1990 and 1991, they were 
even higher than those of domestic enterprises. This is probably 
due to attempts to develop production networks there and to set 
the region up as a manufacturing base for exports to third-party 
countries outside of the region (such as the United States, 
Europe and Japan). In this respect, the region presents the 
following advantages: 
  (1) Labor costs in Asia are much cheaper than in 
economically more advanced countries 
  (2) Many of the manufacturers that have gone to Asia are 
labor-intensive, and depreciation costs and interest payment 
burdens are low. 
  The market for products made by Japanese-owned enterprises 
in 
Asia differs very much from those of Japanese companies in North 
America and Europe: local sales make up no more than slightly 
over half of all sales for Japanese companies in Asia, while 
exports to other countries outside the region, including Japan, 
make up a little under one-half (Table 9.3). 


Table 9.3. Changes in Percent of Products Sold in Local Markets by 
Overseas Japanese Companies: Asia (Unit: percent) 

               1986      1987      1988      1989      1990      1991 

Products for   54.7      59.1      59.8      63.9      59.6      54.5 
local 
markets 

Exports for    45.3      41.0      40.2      36.1      40.4      45.5 
non-local 
markets 

Exports for    15.8      16.7      13.7      15.8      11.8      15.5 
Japanese 
market 


  Demand in Asia, considered the "world center of growth," is 
expected to expand even further in the future, and foreign 
companies, which were drawn to the area at first as a 
manufacturing base for exports to countries outside of the 
region (so-called roundabout exports) will probably be drawn 
increasingly to the area for its own markets. 
  However, even within this "world center of growth," regional 
differences of the type mentioned below are likely to occur, and 
this diversity should be kept in mind. 
  During the second half of the 1980's, Asia's newly 
developing 
economies [NIE's], which received foreign direct investments 
from Japan, all similarly underwent rapid growth. The 1990's, 
however, find Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong and Singapore in 
different political and economic environments. In other words, 
the economies of Taiwan and Hong Kong are in the process of 
merging with the economy of China, which has seen remarkable 
growth through the foreign direct investments of overseas 
Chinese merchants. Singapore's aim is to develop 
knowledge-intensive industries such as service industries and 
banking and financial services. On the other hand, Korea is 
shifting its emphasis from heavy and chemical industries (for 
example, steel and shipbuilding) to high-tech fields such as the 
semiconductor and computer industries. 
  From the end of the 1980's, wages in Asian newly 
industrializing economies soared, off-setting the advantages of 
local production originally undertaken because of their low 
wages. As a result, Japanese foreign direct investments were 
then targeted to ASEAN member countries, which became production 
bases for Japanese manufacturers, especially in the consumer 
appliance and electronics industries for products like air 
conditioners and VTR's. Wages in ASEAN countries have risen 
sharply, however, since 1991, and manufacturers are encountering 
such bottlenecks as inadequate infrastructure provisions and 
difficulties securing engineers and other personnel (these 
countries are having the same problem that Japan has had in 
filling undesirable, so-called 3K positions [jobs considered 
dangerous, difficult and dirty]. At present, ASEAN nations are 
undergoing an adjustment phase in their progress toward 
industrialization. 
  On the other hand, though Japanese direct investments in 
China have been low-pitched due to the Tianamen Square incident 
(June 1989) and to economic adjustment policies, the attention 
of Japanese enterprises at present seem to be focussing on 
China. This is due to such factors since 1991 as: (a) the 
deteriorating investment environment in ASEAN countries and the 
rapid emergence of China, with its conspicuously lower wages, as 
a local production base for Japanese enterprises; (b) the fact 
that, despite concerns about post-Deng Xiaoping political risks, 
China is promoting reform and a policy of openness; and (c) the 
expectation that domestic demand will expand, given China's 
population of 1.1 billion and its huge, potential market. 
<H5>  [Oct 93 pp 15-29] </H5>
  [Excerpts] In the first installment of "Changes in 
Japan's Trade Structure and Foreign Direct Investments" 
(September 1993), we noted that significant changes had occurred 
in Japan's trade structure due to increased foreign direct 
investments during the latter half of the 1980's, including a 
growth in locally manufactured re-import items. Particularly 
noted was the growing importance of Asia as an overseas 
production base. To understand in greater detail (i.e., in micro 
terms) changes in our trade structure given the macro trends 
described earlier, we will look at these changes and trends in 
our foreign direct investments on an industry by industry basis. 
Since foreign direct investments increased during the latter 
half of the 1980's on a global scale, we will take a global 
perspective in considering these structural changes and 
trends. 
<H3>  III. Changes in Trade Structure and Foreign Direct 
Investments as Seen in Different Industries </H3>
  With regard to exports, a look at changes in trade structure 
and foreign direct investments as they apply to the different 
industries (automobiles, consumer appliances and electronics, 
apparel, and steel) generally indicates that, in each of these 
industries, there has been a furthering of local production 
through foreign direct investments (Table 11). However, because 
of difficulties in locally obtaining parts due to the weakness 
of supporting industries, Japan is also exporting more parts 
and, at the same time, is substituting among some of its exports 
finished goods (non-specialty items intended for the general 
market) that have been based on local production. 


Table 11. Changes by Industry in Foreign Direct Investments (Units: $100 million; no. of 
investments) 

Industry                 1986     1987     1988     1989     1990     1991     1992 

Auto/transportation      8.3      14.7     12.8     20.5     18.7     20.0     11.9 
                         (97)     (146)    (128)    (148)    (100)    (60)     (60) 

Consumer                 9.9      24.2     30.4     44.8     56.8     23.0     18.2 
appliance/electronics    (212)    (322)    (316)    (303)    (269)    (209)    (179) 

Textiles                 0.6      2.1      3.2      5.3      8.0      6.2      4.3 
                         (45)     (94)     (146)    (174)    (200)    (242)    (311) 

Steel/nonferrous         3.3      7.9      13.7     15.9     10.5     9.1      8.2 
metals                   (71)     (150)    (194)    (198)    (137)    (124)    (115) 

Source: Ministry of Finance (Monthly Statistical Report, etc.) 

Note: Figures in parentheses ( ) indicate number of investments 


  On the reimport side, in the case of the auto industry, the 
numbers of reimported cars from the United States and elsewhere, 
though still small, are growing. In the apparel and consumer 
appliance and electronics industries, where local production has 
been undertaken primarily to take advantage of low-waged, local 
labor, there has been a steady growth in reimports from Asia 
that have been locally produced. The situation in the steel 
industry, where local production has been undertaken primarily 
as a way of dealing with trade frictions, however, does not 
indicate any growth in reimports based on foreign direct 
investments. 
  1. Auto Industry 
  The auto industry started moving its operations overseas 
from 
the early half of the 1980's, beginning with North America. 
Initially acting in response to voluntary export restrictions, 
the industry speeded this process up from 1985, when the yen 
suddenly gained in value. Local production in Europe started 
from the latter half of the 1980's in response to trade problems 
between the United States and Japan and grew out of the desire 
by Japanese auto makers to gain insider status in light of EC's 
pending economic unification Table 12). 


Table 12. Changes by Region in Foreign Direct Investments by 
Auto/Transportation Industry (Unit: $100 million; no. of investments) 

             1986     1987      1988      1989      1990      1991     1992 

Total        8.3      14.7      12.8      20.5      18.7      20.0     11.9 
[dollar]     (97)     (146)     (128)     (148)     (100)     (60)     (60) 
amount 

North        2.9      7.2       8.1       14.2      5.8       6.9      5.9 
America      (41)     (66)      (76)      (81)      (38)      (21)     (25) 

Europe       0.8      3.0       1.2 (6)   4.4       5.5       7.2      3.9 
             (6)      (11)                (27)      (20)      (16)     (6) 

Asia         1.3      2.1       1.6       1.4       3.7       1.9      1.7 
             (36)     (61)      (35)      (31)      (35)      (21)     (23) 

Source: Ministry of Finance (Monthly Statistical Report, etc.) 

Note: Figures in parentheses ( ) indicate number of investments 


  At first, auto makers had no intention of exporting cars 
back 
to Japan that had been locally produced, but from 1988, 
primarily from concerns about trade friction, they began to 
re-export a small number of passenger cars that had been made in 
the United States and Europe. The number of re-exported cars in 
1992 was 26,000, or about 14 percent of Japan's imported car 
market (of 181,000 cars). 
  The market for passenger cars in Asia (Asian NIE's and ASEAN 
countries, excluding Borneo) is not as large as it is in 
advanced countries (in 1992, 1.448 million cars were sold in 
Asia), but as motorization progresses, Japanese-owned 
enterprises are expected to put more effort into strengthening 
local production. 
  A sharp growth in the export of parts, including car parts 
and engines, has accompanied the development of local production 
bases in regions throughout the world (Table 13). 
  To take the export of passenger cars to the United States as 
an example, we see that, in 1986, 2.348 million cars were 
exported [to the United States], as compared to 508,000 cars 
that were locally produced. In 1992, however, the number of 
exported cars fell to 1.584 million while the figure for locally 
produced cars rose to 1.416 million cars, indicating that 
exports from Japan are being replaced by local production. The 
same trend appears in the EC market. Though the car market has 
been in a slump, operations have begun at plants built through 
Japanese direct investments, and the figures for 1992 show a 
decline in the number of passenger cars being exported from 
Japan. 


Table 13. Changes in Total Exports of Auto-Related Parts (Units: $100 
million; percent change) 

            1986     1987     1988      1989     1990     1991     1992 

Auto        83       107      91        99       109      113      125 
parts 

Growth      57.9     29.8     -14.8     8.4      9.6      4.3      10.7 
rate 

Engines     49       59       67        75       77       83       97 

Growth      30.4     19.5     14.1      10.6     3.7      7.3      16.9 
rate 

Source: Ministry of Finance trade statistics 

Note 1: Figures for auto parts include OEM [original equipment 
manufacturer] exports 

Note 2: Growth rates are based on growth over the previous year 


  2. Consumer Appliance and Electronics Industries 
  The consumer appliance and electronics industries set up 
branch operations in North America, Europe and Asia from a 
relatively early date. Moving into North America and Europe in 
response to trade problems, these industries are eyeing local 
sales in these two regions. In Asia, particularly the ASEAN 
countries, the aim has been to set up export supply 
bases--production bases from which to export products to North 
America and Europe--rather than local sales (Table 14). 


