  With the political situation turning more stable and the 
government adopting a policy of openness and reform, Japanese 
enterprises have also been establishing production bases since 
1990 in China, where labor costs are extremely low. Within 
China, durable consumer goods like refrigerators, washing 
machines and television sets--consumer products that are 
becoming part of the necessities of daily life--are coming into 
general use, and manufacturers are anticipating growth in the 
durable consumer market and products like air conditioners and 
audio-video equipment along with a rise in China's standard of 
living. 
  3. Apparel Industry 
  The apparel industry is labor-intensive, and because it 
became less profitable to export apparel from Japan when the yen 
gained strength following the Plaza Accord, Japanese enterprises 
have gone about aggressively setting up local production 
facilities in Asia in order to utilize the region's relatively 
cheap labor (Table 18). China, where labor costs are especially 
cheap, has emerged as an important production base for mass 
market apparel. At the present time, however, technical 
standards for cloth and dying and quality control are still 
inadequate, and quality control is being handled in Japan. Cut 
cloth is then exported and sewn and assembled locally. Thus, 
there has developed a form of specialization or division of 
labor. 
  Statistical data clearly show changes of this kind with 
regard to Japan's import partners. Until 1990, Korea was the 
apparel industries number one importer; then, from 1991, when 
wages went up and Korea lost its price-competitiveness, China 
assumed that head position (Table 19). 
  While inexpensive (mass market) apparel is being imported 
from Asia, domestic apparel makers are manufacturing expensive 
items (high value added items whose selling point is superior 
design), which cannot be produced overseas, and are thus 
creating a division of labor in terms of imported items and 
domestically manufactured items. 


