  4. Steel Industry 
  In addition to being one of the items subject to managed 
trade and to voluntary export restrictions, steel exports have 
dropped in volume (quantitatively) because they have become less 
price-competitive following the yen's appreciation after the 
Plaza Accord. However, the total dollar amount of steel exports 
has shown very little change, and proportionally more high value 
added items are being exported Table 20). Specifically, while 
high value added export items like surface treated steel 
sheeting (for use in auto bodies and treated to prevent 
corrosion) and special steel materials exports are increasing, 
the export of low value added products like hot rolled steel and 
bar iron is decreasing (Table 21). 
  On the other hand, the trend seems to be toward a steady 
growth in imports from Taiwan and Korea, both in terms of 
quantitative and cash volume. (In 1992, however, there was a 
large drop in import volume because the domestic economy was 
entering an adjustment phase.) Types of steel materials being 
imported are for the most part low value added products like pig 
iron, semi-finished steel ingot products and hot rolled steel 
sheets (Table 22). A comparison of unit prices for imports and 
exports indicates that the latter is about twice that for 
imports, indicating the development of a "segregation of niche" 
(Table 20). 
  In the United States, where the steel industry's primary 
overseas expansion has occurred, Japanese steel makers, 
responding to concerns about U.S.-Japan trade friction, began by 
providing U.S. manufacturers with technical assistance and, at 
present, are undertaking production in the form of mergers with 
U.S. steel manufacturers. This does not mean, however, that 
re-imported steel from the United States has increased; rather 
products manufactured in the United States are being sold on 
the local market. Japanese steel makers have also provided 
technical cooperation to developing nations, and as the 
technical level in those countries improves, inexpensive steel 
will probably start being exported to Japan in earnest (Table 
23.) [passage omitted] 


