                       (10)     (24)     (19)     (16)     (15)     (24) 

Asia           0.6     3.1      2.1      3.1      2.3      2.5      2.6 
               (32)    (95)     (102)    (119)    (79)     (70)     (68) 

Source: Ministry of Finance (Monthly Statistical Report, etc.) 

Note: Figures in parentheses ( ) indicate number of investments 


<H3>  V. Changes in Trade Structure as Seen From the Perspective 
of International Air Cargo </H3>
  From the latter half of the 1980's, a structural change has 
been occurring in Japanese industries, with a move away from 
large-scale and heavy industries (e.g., steel and shipbuilding), 
where there has been declining price competitiveness, toward 
high value added light industries (semiconductors and electronic 
parts, office equipment, scientific and optical equipment, and 
video equipment). Also, with the transfer of production bases 
overseas, there has been an increase in the transport of 
materials and assembly parts as well as maintenance parts to 
service equipment and machinery. In order to meet delivery 
deadlines, air cargo services are being utilized. Moreover, 
along with the global development of horizontal trade 
(intra-industry trade), Japan's volume of high value added 
import products has also increased. 
  Through these changes, there has been a shift (particularly 
noticeable with exports) from surface freight to air cargo in 
terms of international distribution. This shift can be traced, 
using as our indicator the ratio of air cargo export volume to 
total export volume. In terms of the dollar-valued amount of 
this air cargo, too, we can see that, regionally, there has been 
a deepening of economic ties with Asia (Asian NIE's and ASEAN 
countries) where Japanese enterprises have established 
production bases. 
  1. Increasing Ratio of Air Cargo 
  Because there has been a shift in Japan's export structure 
toward high value added industries and, along with foreign 
direct investments by Japanese enterprises, an increase in 
exported parts from Japan, there has also been a steady growth 
in exports shipped as air cargo. Specifically, 1970 figures 
indicate a 4.1 percent growth in the dollar-valued ratio of air 
cargo exports to total exports and a 0.2 percent increase in 
tonnage. By 1992, these ratios had climbed to 15.8 percent and 
0.7 percent, respectively (Table 27). 
  With an increasing volume of high value added imports like 
diamonds, pharmaceutical goods, semiconductors and electronic 
parts and office equipment, there has also been a growth in air 
cargo on the import front. In 1970, the dollar-valued ratio of 
air cargo imports to total imports rose by 7.9 percent and, in 
terms of tonnage, by 0.01 percent. By 1992, these figures had 
grown to 21.1 percent and 0.13 percent, respectively. The 
percentages are low when considering tonnage, but that is 
because heavy raw materials and resources like crude oil and 
liquified natural gas make up a large percentage of Japan's 
import structure (Table 28). 
  Carriage rates for air cargo are about ten times that for 
sea 
freight, so during recessions, companies will send via sea 
rather than air in order to cut down on their operating expenses 
(in other words, in the short term, the ratio of air-to-sea for 
international delivery will be influenced by economic trends). 
Since 1991, when Japan's economy entered an adjustment phase, 
companies have been increasingly conscious of the mounting 
distribution costs associated with just-in-time (JIT) 
deliveries--an accommodation to the small volume, diversified 
product approach taken by manufacturers in recent years--and the 
pressure these costs are placing on profits. In terms of both 
exports and imports, then, there has been a tendency toward 
stagnant or falling growth rates in air cargo and, in fact, for 
two years straight--from 1991 through 1992--the dollar amount of 
air cargo imports fell in absolute terms. From the beginning of 
1993, however, the volume of air cargo imports (in dollars) 
appears to be rising. 
  In terms of predominant trends, we can expect Japan's 
manufactured exports to shift toward high value added products. 
If there is a cut in air cargo rates due to a buildup of air 
cargo carrier capacity, we should be able to see a clear upward 
trend in air cargo ratios as the domestic economy improves. 


