<H5>  VI. Summary </H5>
  Behind the sharp rise in Japanese foreign direct investments 
and the furthering of local production by Japanese enterprises, 
we can see, as major factors, their response to trade friction 
and the steep rise in the yen's value during the latter half of 
the 1980's. As overseas production began, Japan's trade 
structure also began to undergo significant changes as the 
production of manufactured goods which had lost their 
price-competitiveness shifted from domestic industries to 
overseas bases. Trend has caused concern about the "hollowing 
out" of some of Japan's industries at home. A detailed 
examination of trends within specific industries, however, shows 
an aggressive effort by Japanese enterprises to shift domestic 
production in the direction of high value added manufactured 
items that do not have to be price-competitive. For example, in 
the textile and home electronics industries, high quality items 
(high value added products) are exported after being produced at 
home, while mass market items (low value added products) are 
re-imported to Japan after being made at Japanese-owned 
production plants in developing countries where labor costs are 
low. This kind of "segregation of niche," we can see, is 
developing. 
  Future exchange rates will be a factor, of course, but in 
general, we need not assume that particular industries will lose 
their competitive edge in every item they produced (from low and 
intermediate quality items to high quality items) or that there 
will be a complete hollowing out of those industries. Rather, 
the trend seems to be toward a greater differentiation of roles 
in the production field, with domestic industries specializing 
in high value added, high tech products through the development 
of innovative technology. 
  While the furthering of local production by Japanese 
enterprises is inescapable, the course will not necessarily be 
smooth sailing. It holds out many difficulties, not only in 
terms of production and production management technology but 
also in the "soft" sciences of labor and business management. In 
North America and Europe, where Japanese enterprises were 
initially motivated to move primarily in order to avoid trade 
problems, companies are having a tough time in terms of profits, 
and the situation and future direction of local production there 
warrants careful attention. In Asia, on the other hand, 
companies were motivate by the sound economic desire to seek 
cheap labor and are seeing satisfactory profits. At present, 
North America remains the most important region for Japan in 
terms of local production; but it seems only natural that, with 
the growing, future potential of the Asian market, Japanese 
enterprises will be embarking on overseas corporate strategies 
that stress the importance of Asia. Designating Asia as a 
production base not only means a production base for exports but 
also signifies Asia's transformation into a production base 
targeting local sales as regional demand expands. 

</TEXT>

