<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Labor Ministry's Neutrality on Labor Questioned </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2201194694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 17 Jan 
94 Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2201194694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Tokyo office economic reporter Yasuhiro Suzuki; from the </F>
"Kasumigaseki at the Crossroads" series; part two of a 
three-part series of articles on the Labor Ministry: 
"Ministry's Leadership Questioned"] 
  [Editorial Report] Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 
carries on page five of its 17 January Morning Edition a 
2,100-character article by economic reporter Yasuhiro Suzuki as 
the second installment of a three-part series on the Labor 
Ministry in its "Kasumigaseki at the Crossroads" series. 
  The article reports that despite Labor Minister Chikara 
Sakaguchi's fury at the Economic Planning Agency's [EPA] 7 
January report, entitled "Overwork and Health Hazards," which 
indirectly criticizes the Labor Ministry's failure to implement 
adequate measures to reduce working hours, the ministry chose 
not to protest to the EPA for fear of rekindling a controversy 
between labor and management on the issue. 
  Suzuki writes that the cornerstone of the Labor Ministry's 
postwar labor policy is to maintain political neutrality between 
labor and management, although, admittedly, the labor minister 
sometimes works behind the scenes to bring about agreement 
between the two sides during the spring labor offensives. As a 
result, spring offensives over the years have always agreed on a 
wage level commensurate to obtaining economic conditions. 
  However, Suzuki observes that under the current coalition 
government, labor has gained more influence -- for instance, a 
rule limiting weekly working hours to 46 was passed in December 
despite protests from management. Moreover, with the present 
pressing labor issues, such as unemployment and reduced working 
hours amid the economic recession, the Labor Ministry's stance 
of complete political neutrality is now being questioned. The 
ministry is now being asked to exercise leadership in labor 
issues, which it hesitates to do for fear of provoking the 
promanagement Liberal Democratic Party. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

