<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Speech to U.S. University Outlined </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0102140694 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 1 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0102140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa is scheduled to 
deliver a speech to Georgetown University in Washington on 11 
February during his visit to the United States to hold a 
Japan-U.S. summit meeting. The outline of the prime minister's 
speech was worked out on 31 January. While keeping in mind the 
passage of political reform bills through the Diet, the prime 
minister will display his attitude toward tackling domestic 
affairs from the viewpoint that "reform in domestic politics is 
indispensable for promoting diplomacy." For example, he will 
declare that the Hosokawa cabinet intends to continue to tackle 
the task of "promoting reform" as the administration's top 
priority. His speech can be described as a "Hosokawa vision" 
which indicates what Japan ought to be like to prepare for the 
21st century. In concrete terms, Prime Minister Hosokawa will 
clearly state his intention to speed up the following tasks: 1) 
securing transparency in procedures for deciding on government 
policies; and 2) changing the current economic structure to a 
consumer-oriented one. Moreover, the prime minister will call 
for building "stable and strong relations between Japan and the 
United States." He will also spell out his intention to 
strengthen the cooperative relationship between the two 
countries in view of building a new order in the Asia-Pacific 
region in the post-Cold War era. The prime minister's speech 
will last about 20 minutes. He will deliver the speech in 
English as he did at the meeting of the UN General Assembly last 
September. 

</TEXT>

