<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Quad' Powers Agree To Create World Trade Body </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0102010994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0020 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102010994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, Jan 31 KYODO -- Senior trade negotiators 
from the so-called "quad" economic powers have reached a 
provisional agreement to establish the proposed World Trade 
Organization (WTO) on January 1, 1995, trade sources said Monday 
[31 January]. 
  The pact under the Uruguay round of multilateral trade 
talks, 
completed December 15, calls for the creation of a more powerful 
world trade watchdog by July 1, 1995. But its establishment has 
been quickened at the request of the secretariat of the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 
  The United States and Canada have already accepted the 
request, while the European Union has indicated its approval. 
Japan has not lodged any objections to the idea. 
  The sources said the only uncertainty remains over the 
timing 
of the body's creation, despite the agreement between the four 
groups, because each of over 100 participating parties needs to 
ratify the proposal. 
  Also at the four-way talks, the U.S. urged Japan to reopen 
negotiations on proposals to scrap or reduce tariffs on four 
items. 
  The sources said Japan resisted U.S. pressure, citing the 
tariff problems already resolved at the Uruguay round of talks. 
But they said the U.S. is likely to restate its point when U.S. 
Trade Representative Mickey Kantor arrives in Tokyo for trade 
talks Tuesday. 
  The U.S. has proposed ending tariffs on wood products, 
copper 
and white liquor and a tariff cut for leather products. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

