<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   South's Protest on Rice Market Opening Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0202044594 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0436 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0202044594 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["20,000 S. Koreans Protest Agricultural Market Opening" -- </F>
KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, February 2 (KCNA) -- More than 20,000 
farmers and students of South Korea held a peasants' rally 
against the anti-national agricultural market opening by the Kim 
Yong-sam traitorous group at university quarters in Seoul on 
February 1, according to radio reports from Seoul. 
  Sponsored by nine peasants' organisations including the 
National Federation of Peasants Associations (Chonnong), the 
ralliers denounced with bitter indignation the treacherous crime 
of the Kim Yong-sam puppet regime in selling off the markets of 
rice and other agricultural products to the United States. 
  In the resolution adopted at the rally, they said if the 
agricultural market is opened, the South Korean agriculture will 
go totally bankrupt and urged the authorities to put the market 
opening issue to a referendum. And they demanded that the 
"National Assembly" refuse to "ratify" the treacherous 
agricultural market opening. 
  At the end of the rally, they went over to a demonstration, 
loudly shouting "oppose agricultural market opening " and 
marched toward the U.S. Embassy, clashing with a large police 
force. 
  While the demonstrators and police were engaged in a seasaw 
battle, some 500 students of the demonstrators marched toward 
"Chongwadae" [presidential offices]. 
  Synchronising with this protest in Seoul, as many as 200 
peasants of the North Cholla provincial branch of Chonnong 
headed for Seoul to join in it, while staging a demonstration on 
the Seoul-Pusan express highway. 
  Yi Ki-taek, chairman of the opposition Democratic Party, 
called upon politicians and people to join hands in the struggle 
against agricultural market opening. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

