<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Royal Tomb of Founder of Ancient Korea Rebuilt </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0102053094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0457 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0102053094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, February 1 (KCNA) -- The Royal Tomb of 
Wang Kon, the founder of Koryo, has been rebuilt. Koryo was the 
first unified state of Korea which existed for 475 years from 
918. 
  The tomb situated at the foot of Mt. Songak in Kaesong 
consists of a grand domed grave on three stages of foundation 
stones, a portrait of the king, stone sculptures portraying 
celebrated civil servants and warriors who displayed their 
wisdom and courage at the time of the unification of three 
states, paintings on the fight of the Koryo people and the tomb 
gate and a shrine which represent the then architecture. 
  In front of the tomb gate there stands "monument to the 
reconstruction of the royal tomb of Wang Kon, founder of Koryo" 
handwritten by the great leader President Kim Il-song. 
  The visitors can go into the grave and see the interior and 
mural paintings. A wide range of park lies before the tomb. 
  The rebuilt tomb was opened to the general public with a due 
ceremony Monday. 
  In his address at the ceremony, Yim Su-man, chief secretary 
of the Kaesong municipal committee of the Workers' Party of 
Korea and chairman of the Kaesong municipal people's committee, 
said the Royal Tomb of Wang Kon, the founder of Koryo, was 
rebuilt under the wise guidance and care of the great leader 
Comrade Kim Il-song and the dear leader Comrade Kim Chong-il. 
  "This means that we have restored another valuable cultural 
heritage in order to hand down to the posterity the traditions 
of national history ranging from Kojoson (ancient Korea) founded 
by Tangun, which marked the entry of the Korean nation into an 
era of state, an era of civilization, down to Koryo, the first 
unified state succeeding the powerful state in the east Koguryo 
and Palhae," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

