<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Possible Kandal Province Food Shortage Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0202121294 Phnom Penh AKP in French 1007 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0202121294 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh AKP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Summary] Phnom Penh 2 Feb (AKP) -- According to the local 
agriculture service, Kandal Province could face a shortage of 
34,530 tonnes of foodstuffs in 1994 with the production of the 
past rainy season and the current dry season reaching only 
176,200 tonnes. This is not enough to meet the needs of the 
851,620 persons living in the province. 
  Only four districts -- Phnum Penh, Kandal Stoeng, S'ang, and 
Ponhea Loe -- possess favorable conditions for growing rainy 
season rice while land in other districts along the Mekong river 
is reserved for growing dry season rice and subsidiary crops. 
The province transplanted only 45,230 hectares of assorted 
varieties of rice with an average yield of a tonne and a half 
per hectare in the past rainy season. So far the province has 
planted more than 12,300 hectares of fast-growing rice, or 25 
percent of the plan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

