<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Prasong's Visit to Argentina </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0202022694 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 2 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> BK0202022694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Thailand and Argentina agreed to increase bilateral 
relations on economics, trade and investment and target to boost 
trading volume this year, according to a Foreign Ministry press 
statement released yesterday. 
  The 1994 target was set at US$100-200 million per year from 
the current record of US$66 million, during the discussion held 
last Friday between visiting Foreign Minister Prasong Sunsiri 
and Argentine Acting Foreign Minister Armando Caro, the 
statement said. Thailand's imports from Argentina include 
cotton, steel, aluminium, computer hardware and military goods 
while exports are cloths, textiles, furniture and gems. 
  During the meeting, the Thai side also proposed to form a 
mechanism to provide regular consultations between high-level 
officials of the two countries and exchanges of trade 
representatives and diplomatic officials, said the statement. 
  In a separate discussion with Deputy Foreign Minister 
Ferdinand Enrique Petrella, Argentina briefed Sqn Ldr [Squadron 
Leader] Prasong on the Falklands dispute which escalated into a 
war between Argentina and the United Kingdom in 1981. Both sides 
exchanged opinions on various issues such as the negotiations of 
the Uruguay Round's General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs, the 
cooperation under the Cairns group, the Nuclear Non- 
Proliferation Treaty, and the activities of the Asia-Pacific 
Economic Cooperation, the statement added. 

</TEXT>

