<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa, Kono, Others Meet on Stimulus Package </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202090694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0853 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0202090694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 2 KYODO -- Opposition leader Yohei Kono 
urged Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa on Wednesday [2 February] 
to implement a 15 trillion yen economic stimulus package. Chief 
Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told a news conference that 
Kono, president of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), explained 
his party's economy-spurring program adopted Tuesday. 
  Hosokawa replied that he will try to reflect the LDP's ideas 
as far as possible in the government's stimulus package his 
cabinet is to approve Thursday, Takemura said. The additional 
economic program is expected to amount to 15 trillion to 16 
trillion yen, becoming Japan's largest pump-primer ever. 
  Earlier, Kono told reporters after emerging from talks with 
the premier, "I emphasized it would be a disaster if meaningful 
and substantial stimulus steps were not taken this time," he 
added. 
  During the 90-minute meeting, Hosokawa and Kono agreed on 
the 
need for a successful Japan-U.S. summit in Washington on 
February 11, Takemura said. Hosokawa will meet U.S. President 
Bill Clinton to assess progress in stalemated bilateral trade 
talks. 
  Although the LDP chief pressed a demand for a large-scale 
income tax cut to breathe new life into the stagnant economy, 
there was no discussion on how to offset the tax reduction, 
Takemura said. 
  The government and ruling coalition parties are making 
last-ditch efforts to reach a consensus over whether to link a 
major income tax cut to a future hike in the consumption tax. 
  Hosokawa was accompanied by Foreign Minister and Deputy 
Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata, Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii and 
Takemura. 
  Kono attended the meeting along with Ryutaro Hashimoto, 
chairman of the LDP's Policy Affairs Research Council. 
  Hosokawa and Kono concurred they will hold informal talks in 
the future, as the need arises, Takemura said. 
  The premier said he would like to meet again with Kono after 
returning from the United States to discuss the results of the 
meeting with Clinton, according to the chief cabinet secretary. 
Kono gave no clear response, Takemura said. 
  The LDP leader told reporters he will hold talks with the 
premier if he thinks it will be "meaningful," adding he has no 
plan to meet with Hosokawa on a regular basis. 
  Whether he will meet again with the premier, Kono said, 
depends on how much the LDP's economic stimulus program is 
reflected in the government's package. 

</TEXT>

