<H3> <TI>   Kono: `Timing Is Important' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202071294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0703 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0202071294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 2 KYODO -- The leader of the main 
opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) pressed Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa on Wednesday [2 February] to take urgent 
measures to shore up the languishing Japanese economy. 
  "I told him the timing is important in taking 
economy-spurring measures," Yohei Kono told reporters after 
emerging from a meeting with Hosokawa at the premier's official 
residence. "I also emphasized it would be a disaster if 
meaningful and substantial stimulus steps were not taken this 
time," he added. 
  Kono quoted Hosokawa as replying he will strive to do what 
is 
necessary to boost the economy as early as possible. 
  The Hosokawa cabinet is scheduled to announce Thursday a 
massive economic stimulus package expected to total 15 trillion 
to 16 trillion yen, Japan's largest pump-primer ever, to cope 
with the economic slump. Although the premier explained that 
his government and ruling coalition parties are in the final 
stage of building consensus on a large-scale income tax cut, he 
did not touch on how the government proposes to finance the tax 
reduction, Kono said. 
  On Japan-U.S. relations, Kono said he stressed the 
importance 
of Hosokawa having a successful summit with U.S. President Bill 
Clinton next week. 
  The Japanese and U.S. leaders will meet in Washington on 
February 11 to assess progress in the bilateral framework trade 
negotiations. 
  In the meeting with Kono, Hosokawa was accompanied by 
Foreign 
Minister and Deputy Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, Finance 
Minister Hirohisa Fujii and Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi 
Takemura. 
  Kono attended the meeting along with Ryutaro Hashimoto, 
chairman of the LDP's Policy Affairs Research Council. 
  Asked about possible future meetings with Hosokawa, Kono 
replied he will confer with the premier if he thinks it will be 
"meaningful," adding he has no plan to hold such talks on a 
regular basis. 

</TEXT>

