<H3> <TI>   SDPJ Officials Urge Quitting Coalition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202140894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1352 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0202140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 2 KYODO -- Some senior officials of the 
Social Democratic Party (SDP) [of Japan] [SDPJ] on Wednesday [2 
February] urged that the party quit the seven-party coalition 
government of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, SDP sources 
said. At a meeting of the party's policy-making Central 
Executive Committee, the officials expressed strong opposition 
to a government proposal to rename the consumption tax to 
"welfare-purpose" tax and raise the rate from the present 3 
percent to 7 percent, the sources said. 
  Among the opponents was Shun Oide, a party vice chairman, 
the 
sources said. 
  The Hosokawa cabinet, launched last August, includes six 
ministers from the SDP, the largest of the seven ruling parties. 
They are Transport Minister Shigeru Ito, Construction Minister 
Kozo Igarashi, Home Affairs Minister Kanju Sato, National Land 
Agency Director General Kosuke Uehara, Economic Planning Agency 
Director General Manae Kubo and Sadao Yamahana, minister in 
charge of political reform. 

</TEXT>

