<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Cited on Chances for Completing Inspections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0202092694 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0800 GMT 2 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0202092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [AFP/YONHAP from Vienna] </F>
  [Text] The International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] 
disclosed on 1 February that the possibility of completing 
inspections of North Korea's nuclear facilities before the IAEA 
Board of Governors meeting slated for 21 February are becoming 
thinner and thinner. IAEA officials pointed out that even if an 
inspection team leaves for Pyongyang at the end of this week, 
there is not enough time for even submitting a preliminary 
report to the IAEA Board of Governors meeting. The IAEA 
officials said that North Korea has assumed a firm stance on a 
third round of IAEA-North Korea negotiation for nuclear 
inspections. They stressed, however, that the IAEA has not yet 
given up all hope and that the door is still open for North 
Korea. 

</TEXT>

