<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opening Market to Japanese Culture Ruled Out </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0202080294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0715 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0202080294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 2 (YONHAP) -- The government and the 
ruling Democratic Liberal Party (DLP) decided Wednesday not to 
study opening the Korean market to Japanese cultural products, 
an issue raised by the recent remarks of South Korean Ambassador 
to Japan Kong No-myong. 
  Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu told a joint meeting of the 
government and ruling party officials for foreign affairs that 
the remarks of Ambassador Kong are not the official position of 
the Foreign Ministry. Kong said Monday that the present ban on 
Japanese culture should be lifted soon in light of the current 
age of advanced telecommunications and mass media, which is 
rendering borders insignificant. Kong said, "it is desirable 
for Korea to open its markets now to good Japanese cultural 
products including movies." 
  Paek Nam-chi, the party's policy coordinator, quoted 
Minister 
Han as saying at the meeting, "the government is not studying 
the issue of market opening to Japanese cultural products at 
this stage." 
  Paek said, "the joint meeting agreed that studying 
importation of Japanese culture is not feasible at this stage 
because it could pave the way for a flood of foreign culture. 
And considering the special national sentiment toward Japan, it 
is not desirable either, as most participants agreed. The DLP 
is therefore opposed to any cultural market opening." 
  The party's position is to refrain from mentioning the issue 
anymore, as the Foreign Ministry has decided not to study 
opening the market, he added. 
  Meanwhile, DLP chairman Kim Chong-pil told journalists on 
Tuesday that now is not the time to begin importation of 
Japanese culture considering the national sentiment. He 
clarified his opposition to the issue, saying that the country 
should take a prudent attitude toward allowing in Japanese 
culture. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

