<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Georgetown University Speech Previewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202132294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1309 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0202132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 2 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa will stress his commitment to continued political, 
economic and administrative reform in a speech to be delivered 
at Georgetown University in Washington next week, government 
sources said Wednesday [2 February]. The sources said Hosokawa 
will make a commitment to continuing the process of change now 
that his administration has successfully tackled its top 
priority task, with the passage of political reform bills 
through the Diet. 
  Hosokawa leaves for Washington on February 10 for talks with 
U.S. President Bill Clinton the following day. 
  The sources said he will also call for a strengthening of 
the 
Japan-U.S. relationship, underlining the two countries' vital 
roles in the world economy and in ensuring peace and stability 
in the Asia-Pacific region. 
  Hosokawa will deliver a 15-minute speech in English just as 
he did last September at the U.N. General Assembly session, the 
sources said. As his audience will consist mainly of university 
students, Hosokawa will open the floor to questions after his 
speech. 
  He will emphasize his efforts to achieve domestic political 
reform because it is a precondition for meeting the widespread 
expectations that Japan make greater international 
contributions. The prime minister will stress his intention to 
further promote deregulation, take into account the interests of 
consumers and establish a system whereby policy decision-making 
is more transparent. 
  Hosokawa is also scheduled to make a television appearance, 
when he will have the opportunity to address the American public 
directly. 

</TEXT>

