<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Source' Says Pyongyang Wants To Join APEC </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302091594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0846 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302091594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, Feb. 3 KYODO -- A high-level North Korean 
official has said his country is willing to join the 
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum and develop 
contacts with capitalist countries, an East European source in 
Beijing said Thursday [3 February]. 
  Kim Chong-u, deputy chairman of North Korea's External 
Economy Commission, vowed in a conversation with a high-ranking 
East European diplomat last month to attract foreign investment 
through wider contacts with such countries, the source said. 
  According to the source, Kim said North Korea is willing to 
develop ties regardless of their political systems, "as long as 
these countries do not object to our political system." 
  "If we can limit our excessive military expenditure, which 
is 
a heavy burden to our economic development, North Korea could 
quite quickly revitalize the economy and raise the standard of 
living of its society," he was quoted as saying. 
  Kim claimed Pyongyang recently began talks with several 
major 
U.S. and Japanese auto manufacturers, pharmaceutical and oil 
firms, the source said. 
  The deputy chairman, who also supervises the Nachin-Sonpong 
Free Economic Trade Zone in the Tumen River Delta, blamed 
military spending and the collapse of the "socialist camp and 
socialist market" for North Korea's economic difficulties, the 
source said. 
  Kim, 52, considered a strong reform-minded leader, said, 
"North Korea would like to join APEC and benefit from the fact 
that it is located in Asia, the fastest growing region in the 
world." 
  Last December the nation's economic policy was declared a 
failure at a plenary session of the Workers' Party and one based 
on development of agriculture, light industry and trade, and 
strong foreign trade was implemented. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-28036 </DOCNO>
