<H3> <TI>   Japanese Report on `Comfort Women' Cited </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0302122194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1037 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0302122194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, February 3 (KCNA) -- The director of the 
South Korean council for measures on the volunteer corps 
question January 29 stated that five South Korean women who had 
been forced to serve the army as "comfort women" decided to 
bring a suit at the Tokyo district public prosecutor's office, 
according to the Japanese paper MAINICHI SHIMBUN. 
  They said the Japanese imperialists' act of forcing women to 
serve the army as "comfort girls," which deprived them of the 
last vestige of self-respect and trust in humanity was fiendish 
crime unprecedented in human history, and demanded that the 
Japanese prosecution punish those responsible for the 
establishment of the system of "comfort women for the army" and 
the assaulters, said the paper. 

</TEXT>

