<H3> <TI>   Mexican Paper Writes on WPK `Independent Policy' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0202045194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0442 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0202045194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, February 1 (KCNA) -- The professor of the 
Puebla State University of Mexico, Miguel Alba Vega, recently 
dedicated an article titled "Independent Policy of WPK [Workers' 
Party of Korea]" to the paper CAMBIO. 
  The independent policy of the Workers' Party of Korea for 
the 
accomplishment of the socialist cause is expressed in working 
out all lines of the revolution and construction in the interest 
of its people and in conformity with the realities of its 
country. The article said, and went on: 
  However good the experiences of other countries may be, 
President Kim Il-song never introduces them if they are not 
suitable to the realities of his country and the interest of his 
people. 
  Korea firmly maintained the line of building a 
self-supporting national economy when the revisionists forced it 
to enter an economic league, advertising about profitableness. 
  It is thanks to the wise leadership of the president that 
the 
WPK has had no a slightest deviation in its nearly 50-year-long 
guidance to the revolution and construction. 
  The independent policy of the WPK is also expressed in 
solving all problems arising in the revolution and construction 
on the principle of self-reliance. 
  The president, believing in the people and depending on 
them, 
led the anti-Japanese revolutionary struggle and the fatherland 
liberation war against the U.S. imperialists to victory as well 
as the construction of a new country after the liberation, the 
post-war rehabilitation and construction and the socialist 
revolution to victory. 
  The WPK's independent policy is surely guaranteed by the 
principle of chuche in ideology, independence in politics, 
self-sustenance in economy and self-reliance in defence. 
  The Democratic People's Republic of Korea has now turned 
into 
a socialist country steadily developing on its own foot, not 
being subordinate or dependent. 
  This is the result of the independent policy with which the 
Korean people value independence and dignity more than their 
lives and allow nobody to trample down national independence. 

</TEXT>

