<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Reportedly Rejects Nuclear Inspections </TI></H3>
<H4>   IAEA Responds to Report </H4>
<F P=102> SK0302094794 Seoul KBS-1 Television Network in Korean 0835 
GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0302094794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday, North Korea sent a statement to the 
International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] saying it rejected 
full-scope [chonmyon] inspections, as reported by Japan's NHK 
Broadcast in a Berlin-datelined story. 
  By sending its 31 January statement to the IAEA saying that 
it will withdraw from the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty unless 
the United States stops its scheme to crush the Pyongyang side, 
North Korea stated that the fact that the United States and the 
IAEA urge North Korea to receive full-scope inspections of its 
nuclear facilities violates the spirit of the North Korea-U.S. 
agreement, and revealed that it will not negotiate further with 
the IAEA unless the agreement mapped out in New York is kept. 
  Responding to this, IAEA spokesman Meyer said the IAEA does 
not regard a protest document sent by North Korea as an official 
answer and that the IAEA is still waiting for North Korea's 
official response to its specification inquiring about the place 
and schedule for nuclear inspections. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

