<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador to U.S. Denies Position Differences </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0302090194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0848 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0302090194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 3 (YONHAP) -- South Korean Ambassador 
to the United States Han Sung-su said on Thursday there is no 
difference between Seoul and Washington's positions on the North 
Korean nuclear problem. Han, who is attending the annual 
conference of Korean ambassadors and envoys here, said the two 
nations' relationship is strong enough to weather any attempt to 
destroy it. He expected that the North Korean nuclear problem 
will be discussed by the United Nations Security Council after 
March 21. 
  If the Board of Governors' meeting of the International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), slated for March 21, comes to the 
conclusion that the continuity of North Korea's nuclear 
safeguards can no longer be assured, the issue will have to be 
discussed by the U.N. Security Council, he said. 
  "Then, the council will discuss everything about the (North 
Korean nuclear) problem including sanctions against North 
Korea," he said. 
  He urged Pyongyang to make a rational judgement, saying that 
the North Koreans themselves know very well that the issue will 
be transferred to the U.N. Security Council if the IAEA Board 
of Governors' meeting fails to solve the problem. He also 
confirmed that there are no problems with South Korean security. 
He denied U.S. reports that tension on the Korean peninsula is 
mounting, saying that South Korea's security has not 
deteriorated and is in fact no different from the past. 
  Meanwhile, discussions on deployment of U.S. Patriot 
missiles in South Korea are under way between the South Korean 
and U.S. Governments, and the two have agreed that deployment of 
the anti-missile missiles should not affect the IAEA-North 
Korean negotiations, Han said. 
  The reason why the IAEA and North Korea cannot narrow their 
differences is not the possibility that Patriot missiles will be 
deployed in South Korea, but that they differ on technical 
problems related to nuclear inspections, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

