<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Accused of Hypocrisy Regarding Arms Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0302031794 Seoul MAEIL KYONGJE SINMUN in Korean 3 Feb 94 p 
8 </F>

<F P=103> SK0302031794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul MAEIL KYONGJE SINMUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Yi Chong-hyon: "The Two Faces of the U.S.--the </F>
Police and the Arms Dealer"] 
  [Text] The "world's police" that always talks about peace 
and imposing sanctions on countries selling weapons, the United 
States is, in fact, the greatest arms trader. The United 
States' sensitivity to the export of weapons by other countries 
is part of their sophisticated strategy to sell their "own 
commodities." 
  The WALL STREET JOURNAL of 28 January reported that "since 
the end of the Cold War, the United States has become the 
greatest exporter of conventional weapons" and that "in 
particular, the United States achieved record weapons sales of 
$340 million last year." Weapons sold by "the police" have 
seeped to third countries where disputes frequently take place 
to become lethal weapons there. 
  The WALL STREET JOURNAL denounced the United States 
regarding 
this for "actively exporting weapons while urging other 
countries to refrain from exporting weapons under the pretext of 
world security." 
  Last year, the United States assumed a hard-line attitude 
and 
imposed trade sanctions on China for exporting missiles to 
Pakistan. Even though China strongly denied the charge, world 
opinion supported the "defense of peace" position of the United 
States that strong measures be taken against suspected 
arms-selling countries. Although an excuse, the cause of world 
peace seemed plausible. However, according to the WALL STREET 
JOURNAL's report, the United States sold a total of 484 missiles 
in the five years from 1989 to 1992. This is almost eight times 
the 63 missiles China exported. 
  It is unreasonable for the United States to strongly slander 
China for arms sales which are so slight in comparison to its 
own sales, and it is unreasonable for it to do so under the 
pretext of peace while continuing its own sales. 
  It has been learned that arms dealers even manipulated 
disputes for their own interests. The world is anxiously 
watching the two faces --"police" and arms dealer--of the United 
States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

