<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Ease Rules on Overseas Fund-Raising </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0302032394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0135 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0302032394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 3 (YONHAP) -- The government will ease 
restrictions on corporate fund-raising overseas by increasing 
the ceiling on foreign exchange-denominated securities issues 
abroad from last year's 2 billion U.S. dollars to 2.5 billion 
dollars and relaxing the qualifications required of corporations 
to issue such foreign debts. 
  Finance Minister Hong Chae-hyong, attending a meeting of 
business leaders sponsored by the Korea Employers' Federation on 
Wednesday, said the government would also selectively allow the 
introduction of foreign commercial loans to finance imports of 
capital goods for infrastructure expansion projects. 
  To help corporate investment in foreign countries, 
restrictions on overseas real estate investment will be eased, 
while the red tape surrounding government approval of corporate 
foreign investment plans will be removed. In addition, overseas 
securities investment by institutional investors, such as 
securities houses and insurance companies, will be liberalized, 
Hong said. 
  To improve the country's foreign investment environment, he 
added, the five-year industry-by-industry plan on market opening 
for foreign investors, set to start in 1996, will be revised to 
advance the opening date and broaden the opening scope. 
  The increased investment in foreign industries and 
securities 
markets will check inflation due to an anticipated increase in 
foreign fund inflows in the coming year, he observed. 
  Foreign investors are expected to increase their 
participation in the stock market here this year, combining with 
a current-account surplus expected for the year to expand 
foreign fund flows to the country. 
  Corporations giving employees part of their profits in the 
form of a special bonus in shares, not in cash, will be accorded 
tax benefits in a bid to promote labor peace in such 
corporations, Hong said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

