<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shipping Firms Allowed To Obtain Vessels Abroad </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0302125194 Seoul YONHAP in English 1053 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0302125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 3 (YONHAP) -- Korean shipping lines are 
enabled to obtain large specialized vessels or container ships 
through their locally incorporated firms abroad effective April 
this year. The Maritime and Port Administration reported on 
Thursday it had decided to permit shipping firms to build these 
vessels with foreign financial funds obtained in the name of 
their locally incorporated companies. 
  The decision is to help the maritime industry secure vessels 
more easily and alleviate their taxational burdens, an official 
at the administration said. He explained that Korean shipping 
firms will be allowed to obtain shipbuilding loans abroad 
without regard to whether the vessels to be built would be 
registered in Korea or elsewhere. This means that ships thus 
obtained could be registered in third countries, instead of 
Korea, where ship-related tax rates are lower. 
  In the initial stage, shipping lines will be permitted to 
obtain only large specialized vessels like crude oil, coal and 
iron ore carriers and container vessels because an overall 
permission would obviously lead to a rush to overseas vessel 
procurement, the official said. 
  Presently shipping lines obtain vessels with either 
shipbuilding loans from domestic banks or foreign capital 
introduced under the condition of registering new-built vessels 
in the country. But, domestic loans carry high interest rates 
while introduction of foreign capital has to go through rigid 
government control. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

