<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sanctions `May Be Unavoidable' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302090894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0859 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302090894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 3 KYODO -- U.S. Trade Representative 
Mickey Kantor suggested Thursday [3 February] trade sanctions 
may be unavoidable if a compromise cannot be reached with Japan 
over establishing numerical targets in bilateral trade relations. 
  Kantor asked leaders of the opposition Liberal Democratic 
Party (LDP) for their understanding in the trade framework 
negotiations, saying that without numerical targets in the 
automotive, insurance and other fields, the U.S. choices of 
action would be limited. 
  Kantor met LDP Secretary General Yoshiro Mori and Ryutaro 
Hashimoto, a former finance minister and now chairman of the 
LDP's Policy Affairs Research Council. 
  Mori, in response, explained Japan's efforts to open its 
markets but added the idea of numerical targets would have a 
negative effect on international free trade. 
  The LDP leaders expressed support for the government's 
direction in the trade negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-28096 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas023_a_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-023 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nations `Must Continue To Try' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0302093694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0927 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302093694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 3 KYODO -- U.S. Trade Representative 
Mickey Kantor and Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa agreed 
Thursday [3 February] that the United States and Japan must 
continue to try to achieve progress in bilateral trade talks, 
the top government spokesman said. 
  The two were meeting at the premier's official residence, 
Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told a news 
conference. 
  "They agreed that it is important for both sides to make 
further efforts" ahead to the meeting between U.S. President 
Bill Clinton and Hosokawa in Washington on February 11, Takemura 
said. 
  Hosokawa will confer with Clinton to assess progress in the 
economic talks being held under a bilateral accord concluded 
last July. 
  Kantor expressed hope the Clinton-Hosokawa meeting will help 
the bilateral trade negotiations bear fruit, Takemura said. 
  The U.S. administration hopes to successfully conclude the 
framework talks prior to the summit of the two leaders, who met 
twice last year. 
  Negotiations on automobile and auto parts trade, government 
procurement and foreign access to the Japanese insurance market 
have been stalemated over a U.S. proposal on setting "objective 
criteria" to gauge the openness of Japanese markets. 
  Tokyo has refused to accept the proposal, saying such 
measures would amount to setting aside a specific market share 
for foreign goods and services, tantamount to managed trade. 
  Kantor, who came to Tokyo on Tuesday as Clinton's special 
envoy, did not directly voice dissatisfaction with Tokyo's 
stance. 
  On the government's announcement of a 5.3 trillion yen 
income 
tax cut, Kantor said it was an appropriate decision but did not 
elaborate, Takemura said. 
  Kantor congratulated Hosokawa on his success in getting onto 
the statute books a set of political reform bills aimed at 
rooting out corruption in Japanese public life, according to the 
chief cabinet secretary. 
  Hosokawa narrowly pushed through his reforms, on which he 
had 
staked his political fortunes, by his stated deadline of 
Saturday, the closing date of the last extraordinary Diet 
session. 
  On his arrival at the premier's official residence, Kantor 
told KYODO NEWS SERVICE that he welcomes Tokyo's decision to 
slash income tax by 5.3 trillion yen. 
  "It is a useful step in the right direction," he said. 
  After emerging from his 40-minute meeting with Hosokawa, the 
U.S. trade representative said it was "a very good meeting." 
  W. Bowman Cutter, deputy presidential assistant for economic 
policy, and Takemura were also present at the Kantor-Hosokawa 
talks. 
  Asked if Clinton would move to revive the "Super 301" trade 
measure through an executive order, Kantor said only, "We'll 
save that conversation for later." 
  Kantor said last month the Clinton administration may renew 
the punitive measure through an executive order in connection 
with the deadlocked trade talks between Japan and the United 
States. 
  The super 301, in effect from 1988 to 1990, required the 
U.S. 
Government to conduct an annual review of trade barriers abroad 
and impose trade sanctions if those barriers were not removed 
within a year. 
  On Wednesday, Kantor met with International Trade and 
Industry Minister Hiroshi Kumagai and Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata. He also conferred with Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii 
earlier Thursday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

