<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Subcabinet-Level Talks With U.S. Scheduled </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0202170294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1656 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0202170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 3 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
will hold subcabinet-level meetings in Washington next week to 
seek a breakthrough in the deadlocked bilateral trade talks, 
government sources said Wednesday [2 February]. 
  The two countries decided against holding the high-level 
talks this weekend in Tokyo as originally planned because the 
prospect of an early breakthrough is dim, the sources said. 
  U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor met Japanese Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata and International Trade and Industry 
Minister Hiroshi Kumagai on Wednesday, but the two sides failed 
to narrow the gap over the U.S. demand that numerial targets be 
set to measure progress in opening Japanese markets to foreign 
products. 
  Japanese and U.S. officials are supposed to draw up a 
progress report on the framework trade talks before Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and U.S. President Bill Clinton meet 
February 11. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

