<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Tax Reform Proposal Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Saito: Tax Barely Balances Cuts </H4>
<F P=102> OW0302110294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1054 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0302110294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 3 KYODO -- The 7 percent rate decided 
for the new welfare tax just barely meets the required amount 
needed to balance planned income and residential tax cuts worth 
6 trillion yen, a top Finance Ministry official said Thursday [3 
February]. 
  Vice Finance Minister Jiro Saito told a regular press 
meeting 
that if the rate is lowered to 6 percent, the amount of tax cuts 
must also be reduced. 
  "Bond redemptions become impossible with a 6 percent rate, 
an 
8 percent rate generates more than enough revenue," he said. 
  Saito also said his ministry is "not thinking of raising the 
rate (on the new tax) in the future." 
  Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa decided early Thursday on a 
new tax plan, calling for the tax cuts, including 5.3 trillion 
yen in income tax cut and adoption of a new "national welfare" 
tax in three years to replace the current 3 percent consumption 
tax. 
  But the decision, which was made without the approval of the 
Social Democratic Party (SDP), the largest in the ruling 
coalition, appears to be set for revision due to that party's 
strong opposition. 
  Saito brushed aside reports that the ministry led the 
government to decide on the plan, saying the naming, timing and 
scope of the new tax were decided by leaders of the coalition 
parties. 
  The ministry just answered their "technical questions," he 
said. 
  With the political row delaying announcement of the 
government's economic stimulus package, which is due Thursday 
evening, Saito said he hopes the package will be implemented "as 
early as possible." 
  Admitting for the first time that past fiscal measures led 
by 
additional public works projects failed to lift the economy, 
Saito said, "the economy remained weak" after only implementing 
public works projects and "we pin hopes on the income tax cut 
(as a means of strengthening the economy)." 

</TEXT>

